Remember that to apply the STL decomposition certain conditions need to be fulfilled, so you may need to manipulate the time series.

#SOLUTION
# Obtain the suggested value for lambda
l <- cafes %>%
  features(Turnover, features = guerrero) %>%
  pull(lambda_guerrero)

# Inspect the transformed series
cafes %>% 
  autoplot(box_cox(Turnover, lambda = l))

# Perform the decomposition

Answer briefly (max 75 words per question. You may use less than 75 words as well).

  • Compare the autocorrelation graph of the total time series and the seasonally-adjusted series.
    • Are they similar to one another? Why? Why not?

Both graphs are very similar. This is due to the fact that the seasonal component is much smaller than the trend component. The seasonally-adjusted component (remainder + trend) is therefore not much different from the total time series.

  • Does the series exhibit seasonality? Focus on the values of the autocorrelation on multiples of the seasonal period.
    • If so, in which graph did you spot the seasonality?

Examining the autocorrelation graph of the seasonal component, we see that the series exhibits yearly seasonality. This can be recognized in the spikes at lags 12, 24, 36 (multiples of 12) on the seasonal component.

5. (1 point) Fit the following models to each of the training datasets:

  • Naive model
  • Simple Exponential Smoothing
  • Mean model
  • Seasonal Naive model
  • decompositoin_model() with:
    • STL decomposition applied to decompose the time series.
      • Note: if you managed to find good parameters for the decomposition in question 2, use those. Otherwise use the defaults.
    • Drift model applied to the seasonally adjusted component.
    • SNaive model applied to the seasonal component.
#SOLUTION
fit_tr60 <- train_60 %>%
              model(
                naive_60 = NAIVE(Turnover),
                SES_60 = ETS(Turnover ~ error("A") + trend("N") + season("N")),
                mean_60 = MEAN(Turnover),
                snaive_60 = SNAIVE(Turnover),
                decomp_stl_60 = decomposition_model(
                             # Specify decomposition scheme to be used
                             STL(box_cox(Turnover, lambda = l) ~ trend(window = 5) + season(window=5)),
                             # Specify model for the seasonally adjusted component
                             RW(season_adjust ~ drift()),
                             # Specify model for the seasonal component (unnecessary since SNAIVE is default)
                             SNAIVE(season_year)
                             )
              )

fit_tr80 <- train_80 %>%
              model(
                naive_80 = NAIVE(Turnover),
                SES_80 = ETS(Turnover ~ error("A") + trend("N") + season("N")),
                mean_80 = MEAN(Turnover),

7. (1 point) Answer the following questions regarding the output of question 6

Questions (answer briefly, max 75 words per question but be as succint as possible):

  • What is the forecast horizon of the residuals for which the metrics have been computed in 6?

The metrics have been computed based on the residuals. Residuals are one-step ahead forecasts computed on the training dataset. Therefore we could say that the above metrics are based on a one-step horizon.

  • What are the units of the MAE? What does it represent?

The units of the Mean Absolute Error are the same as the units of the time series. In this case $Million AUD.

As its name indicates it is simply the mean of the absolute errors of the forecasts.

  • What are the units of the RMSE?

The units of the Root Mean Squared Error are the same as the units of the time series. In this case, again $Million AUD.

Instead of taking the absolute value as in the MAE, the RMSE works with the squared errors to ensure positive and negative errors do not cancel each other out when averaging. After avering these errors, taking the square root yields the RMSE.

  • What are the units of MAPE? What does it represent?

The Mean Absolute Percentage Error has no units. It is the mean of the percentage errors, which are unitless because the units in the numerator and the denominator cancel each other out:

\[ p_{t} = 100 e_{t}/y_{t} \]

Being unitless these error metrics may be used to compare the performance of forecast methods between different datasets.

  • Which is the best performing model in terms of RMSE? Clarify how you have determined this.

Based on the metrics performed on the training dataset (based on the residuals), the best performing model is decomp_stl_60. This may be seen on the table above, where it is clear that this model has the smallest RMSE.

  • For a given error metric and model type (naive, decomposition, SES), do the results change with the training dataset? Why or why not?

Yes. We may see this by comparing the metrics of each model on the training dataset containing 60 and 80 percent of the observations. * The main reason for this is that the time series itself might be behaving different at each cut-out point. * The second reason is the different manner in which the model fits each dataset. In this case the models have so little parameters (or even no parameters) that this is not the likely cause.

8. (0.5 points) For the best model in terms of RMSE of the residuals, assess and interpret the autocorrelation of the residuals (max 75 words but be as succint as possible).

#SOLUTION
fit %>% 
  select(decomp_stl_60) %>% # Selects the best model in terms of RMSE
  gg_tsresiduals()
## Warning: Removed 12 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 12 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 12 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

# Box-Pierce Statistic
fit %>% 
  select(decomp_stl_60) %>% # Selects the best model in terms of RMSE
  augment() %>% 
  features(.innov, box_pierce, lag = 24, dof = 1)
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   .model        bp_stat bp_pvalue
##   <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>
## 1 decomp_stl_60    114.  4.70e-14

Desipte decomp_60 being the model that behaves best in terms of the RMSE of its residuals, its residuals actually exhibit signs of autocorrelation. This means that there is information left in the residuals that decomp_60 does not account for, and therefore we can positively say that the model is improvable.

On the other hand, if a model does not show autocorrelation in its residuals, it does not mean that it cannot be improved.

  • The training datasets shall increase in steps of 5 observations.
  • The goal is to obtain summary metrics for each model type and forecast horizon. Retain the MAE, the RMSE and the MAPE.
    • Arrange your results from smallest to largest RMSE

After you have performed the computations, some questions follow:

                             # Specify model for the seasonal component (unnecessary since SNAIVE is default)
                             SNAIVE(season_year)
                             )
              )

fc_cv <- fit_cv %>%
            forecast(h = 12) %>%
            group_by(.id, .model) %>%
            mutate(h = row_number()) %>%
            ungroup() %>%
            as_fable(response = "Turnover", distribution = Turnover)

summary_cv <- fc_cv %>%
                accuracy(cafes, by=c("h", ".model")) %>%
                select(-c(MPE, MASE, RMSSE, ACF1, ME)) %>%
                arrange(RMSE)
## Warning: The future dataset is incomplete, incomplete out-of-sample data will be treated as missing. 
## 10 observations are missing between 2019 Jan and 2019 Oct
bind_rows(
            summary_cv %>% filter(h == 1),
            summary_cv %>% filter(h == 6),
            summary_cv %>% filter(h == 12)
          )

NOTE: to answer these quesitons you might need to filter and or arrange the output of the accuracy() function from your previous answer:

  • For a forecast horizon of 1:
    • Which is the model with smallest RMSE?

The model that performs best in terms of RMSE for h=1 seems to be the decomposition model.

  • Is it the same model type than in question 9?

No, in the foregoing question the best performing model for h=1 was simple exponential smoothing.

  • If they differ, why do they?

They differ because question 9 assessed the performance of the different models over two particular datasets. This makes the results susceptible to behavior differences in the time series at each cut-out point of the training dataset or to differences in the manner the model fits each dataset. Given the low number of parameters of these models, the latter is not the primary factor influencing these differences.

Cross-validation is more statistically robust and assesses the performance over a series of datasets, returning the average performance.

  • For a forecast horizon of 6:
    • Which is the model with smallest RMSE?

The model that performs best in terms of RMSE for h=6 seems to be again the decomposition model.

  • Is it the same model type than in question 9?

It is not the same model than in question 9. The reason is the same one given above.

  • If they differ, why do they?

See above.

  • For a forecast horizon of 12:
    • Which is the model with smallest RMSE?

For a forecast horizon of 12, the naive and snaive model perform best. Their performances match exactly because the seasonal nave model extends the behavior of the latest period into the future while the nave model extends the last value into the future. Therefore, for a forecast horizon equal to the seasonal period (or to an exact multiple of the seasonal period) their performances match.

  • Is it the same model type than in question 9?

It is not the same model than in question 9. The reason is the same one given above.

  • If they differ, why do they?

See above.
